<font color="#FF0000">THANKS GUYS!</font><br>
<tt>Sat Sep  6  1:06:50 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Ed and all the others:<br><br>
You guys are more than just a conversation piece to me too.  I value friendship, and especially yours, Ed.  Sometimes, when I see something I don't like, I express it.  It is only with people whom I have either very high regard, or very high distain, that I feel free to say such things, and you can be assured that I do not have distain for any of you, and that includes Doc Spatz.  Doc Del hasn't been heard from for some time, but he's probably out fishin' or doing something else constructive.  <br><br>
Ed, you and a lot of the other guys have probably done quite a bit more for veterans than have I, and you have my admiration for that.  <br><br>
I will tell you this, this bit of conversation has helped me through a very difficult time with my loosing my job, and the frustrations that has caused within my own family.  We each need an outlet, and being isolated can be very damaging.  Having people with the tenacious support all of you have exhibited has really helped me.  Thank you all.<br><br>
Today I received the score on a job application for a very good State of Oregon job.  With my veteran's points, I scored 105 out of a possible 100 points.  While this doesn't guarantee the job to me, it surely puts me in the running.  I also interviewed for another job last Tuesday.  There's hope!<br><br>
During those times I was a bit distracted from these threads, it was because I was preparring one of the 50 or so job applications I've completed since the first of the year. <br><br>
I know that we all have our little quirks; it's good to see the humor, exasperation, and full range of healthy emotions exhibited here.  These outlets are necessary.  We're all trying to keep our heads out of the water (but I prefer to breath through a snorkel when I'm in the river).<br><br>
Now, so far as pilots go, I think they have far too great a confidence in their helicapeters than is justified by the record of those contraptions falling out of the air (yes Ed, I do know what an autorotation is, and luckily we were 2000 feet over the Columbia River when the engine cut out--damn Reserve HH-34 left over from the Navy).  I'd rather have a parachute anytime.  HoooYaaaa!
<p><code>-- searat@sorcom.com  (John C. Ratliff) </code><p>


